# Wazuh Home SOC Lab

## Overview
The goal of this lab is to simulate real-world cyber attacks, monitor endpoint and network activity, investigate security events, and perform vulnerability assessments.

## Lab Architecture

- Ubuntu Server (Wazuh Manager + Dashboard)
- Kali Linux (Attacker)
- Ubuntu Server (Monitored Endpoint with Wazuh Agent)

## Technologies

- Wazuh SIEM
- Suricata IDS
- Ubuntu Server
- Kali Linux
- Linux
- SSH
- Hydra
- Nmap

## Current Scenarios

- SSH Authentication
- Privilege Escalation
- File Integrity Monitoring
- User Account Creation
- Threat Hunting

## Skills Demonstrated

-Built and configured a multi-VM Security Operations Center (SOC) lab consisting of a Wazuh Manager, Ubuntu endpoint, and Kali Linux attacker to simulate enterprise security monitoring.
-Investigated security events generated by Wazuh SIEM analyzing authentication logs, endpoint telemetry, Suricata IDS alerts, and Linux audit logs to identify suspicious activity and validate detections.
-Simulated SSH brute-force attacks using Hydra and analyzed failed authentication attempts, successful logins, source IP addresses, and event timelines within the Wazuh Dashboard.
-Conducted threat hunting by correlating endpoint and network telemetry to identify reconnaissance activity, privilege escalation attempts, and user account management events.
-Analyzed Suricata IDS alerts generated from Nmap reconnaissance scans to validate intrusion detection and assess attacker behavior.
-Validated File Integrity Monitoring (FIM) by creating, modifying, and deleting monitored files while verifying Wazuh's detection of unauthorized file system changes.
-Investigated Linux privilege escalation and user account creation events by reviewing Wazuh alerts and system logs to confirm security-relevant administrative activity.

## Lab Demonstrations

### SSH Authentication Failure and Success

I used Hydra from my Kali Linux VM to perform an SSH brute-force attack against my Ubuntu agent. Wazuh detected the repeated failed login attempts and generated authentication alerts that I investigated through the Wazuh Dashboard.

![Hydra Result](Screenshots/Hydra%20result.png) 
![Authentication Failure](Screenshots/Authenticatioin%20failure.png)

### File Integrity Monitoring

To test File Integrity Monitoring, I created, modified, and deleted files on the Ubuntu agent. Wazuh detected each change and generated alerts showing the file activity, demonstrating how it can identify unauthorized modifications to monitored files and directories.

![FIM](Screenshots/FIM.png)

---

### Network Reconnaissance

I performed an Nmap scan from my Kali Linux VM against the Ubuntu agent to simulate reconnaissance activity. Suricata detected the scan and forwarded the alert to Wazuh, where I investigated the alert the Wazuh Dashboard.

![Suricata Nmap](Screenshots/Suricata%20NMAP.png)

---

### Privilege Escalation

I simulated privilege escalation by using `sudo` to elevate my privileges on the Ubuntu agent. Wazuh detected the successful elevation to the root account and generated a security event that was analyzed through the dashboard. 

![Privilege Escalation](Screenshots/Privelge%20Escalation%20to%20Root.png)

---

### User Account Creation

To create account management activity, I created and removed a local Linux user on the Ubuntu agent. Wazuh detected both actions and logged the events, demonstrating its ability to monitor changes to user accounts.

![User Creation and Removal](Screenshots/User%20creation%20and%20removal.png)

# What I Learned

Building this lab gave me a much better understanding of how a Security Operations Center (SOC) operates and how security analysts investigate alerts. Before building it, I had learned about SIEMs and threat detection through coursework and labs, but this project gave me the opportunity to put those concepts into practice.

Throughout the lab, I configured Wazuh, integrated Suricata, simulated attacks from my Kali Linux VM, and investigated the resulting alerts through the Wazuh Dashboard.

Working through each scenario helped me better understand how different types of attacker activity appear from a defender's perspective and how a SIEM can be used to investigate suspicious behavior instead of simply generating alerts.

This project also strengthened my Linux skills by managing users, monitoring file changes, working with system services, and troubleshooting security tools.

Overall, this lab made me more confident using Linux, investigating security alerts, and understanding how a Security Operations Center monitors and responds to security events. It also reinforced the importance of approaching cybersecurity from both the attacker and defender perspectives.
